<BaseLayout
  title="About Abe Crystal, PhD | MoreBetterLabs"
  description="Learning design researcher, course platform builder, and educator. PhD in Information Science (HCI) from UNC-Chapel Hill, teaching at UNC SILS, UNC School of Education, and NC State College of Design."
  canonical="/about/"
  schema={[personSchema]}
>
  <section class="pt-20 pb-8 sm:pt-28">
    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-5">
      <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold leading-tight mb-4" style="color: hsl(170 5% 95%);">
        Abe Crystal, PhD
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg" style="color: hsl(170 5% 55%);">
        Learning design researcher, course platform builder, and educator.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="pb-20 sm:pb-28">
    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-5">
      <div class="prose-mbl">
        <h2>Background</h2>
        <p>
          I've spent my career at the intersection of learning science, technology, and design. My PhD research at
          <strong>UNC-Chapel Hill's School of Information and Library Science (SILS)</strong> focused on how people
          organize, access, and use information in educational contexts — work that has directly shaped how I think
          about online course design.
        </p>
        <p>
          My dissertation, <em>Design Research for Personal Information Management Systems to Support Undergraduate
          Students</em> (2008), used field research to understand how students actually manage their learning —
          not how we assume they do. That gap between assumption and reality is what drives everything I build.
        </p>
        <p>
          Before graduate school, I earned my AB in Economics from <strong>Princeton University</strong>.
        </p>

        <h2>Academic Research</h2>
        <p>
          My published research spans human-computer interaction, information architecture, and learning system design.
          Key publications include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>"Augmenting Memory for Student Learning"</strong> (ASIST 2006, with Barreau, Greenberg, Sharma, Conway, et al.) —
            designing context-aware capture systems for biology education. This research directly informed how
            I think about scaffolding and memory support in online courses.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>"Design Research for a Context-Aware Capture System to Support Biology Education"</strong> (DIS 2006) —
            applying design research methodology to educational technology, bridging lab research and real classroom needs.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>"Memex Metadata (M2) for Reflective Learning"</strong> (Dublin Core 2006, with Greenberg, Sharma, et al.) —
            systems that support reflective learning through structured metadata.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>"Facets Are Fundamental: Rethinking Information Architecture Frameworks"</strong>
            (<em>Technical Communication</em>, 2007) — how faceted classification helps people navigate
            complex information.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>"Task Analysis and Human-Computer Interaction"</strong> (AMCIS 2004, with Ellington) —
            methodological foundations for understanding how people actually use educational tools.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Across 13 publications (335+ citations), the through line is the same: understand how people
          actually learn and manage information, then design systems that support those real behaviors.
        </p>

        <h2>Teaching</h2>
        <p>
          I teach and have taught at several universities, which keeps my learning design thinking grounded
          in current educational practice:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>UNC School of Education</strong> — seminars on educational innovation and technology-enhanced learning
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>UNC School of Information and Library Science (SILS)</strong> — information architecture and
            human-computer interaction
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>NC State University, College of Design</strong> — design research methodology applied to
            educational systems and user experience
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Building Ruzuku</h2>
        <p>
          In 2011, I co-founded <a href="https://www.ruzuku.com">Ruzuku</a> — an online course platform
          built from the ground up on learning design principles. The question that drove us wasn't
          "how do we help people sell courses?" but "how do we help people <em>teach</em> courses that
          actually work?"
        </p>
        <p>
          My research on context-aware learning systems, reflective metadata, and information architecture
          directly shaped Ruzuku's design: step-by-step course progression (not content dumps), built-in
          discussion for social learning, structured feedback loops, and a focus on completion over consumption.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since launch, Ruzuku has hosted 75,000+ courses serving over 500,000 students — from coaches
          and wellness practitioners to nonprofits and corporate trainers.
        </p>

        <h2>Writing</h2>
        <p>
          I'm the author of <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Business-Courses-Abe-Crystal/dp/1737374218"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"><em>The Business of Courses</em></a> (2021) and co-host of the
          <a href="https://courselab.co/" rel="noopener noreferrer">Course Lab Podcast</a> with
          Ari Iny. Both are built on the same principle: course creation works best when it's grounded
          in how people actually learn, not just what's easy to record.
        </p>
        <p>
          This site, MoreBetterLabs, is where I write about learning design for practitioners — the
          research and principles behind effective online education, translated into language and
          frameworks that course creators can actually use.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
